7. **[Hugh and Matilda Boyle House and Cemetery Historic District](/Hugh_and_Matilda_Boyle_House_and_Cemetery_Historic_District)** – Encompasses a Victorian‑style residence and an adjacent family burial ground, notable for its **[Gothic Revival](/Gothic_Revival_Architecture)** stained‑glass windows and the preservation of original funerary art.  

8. **[Brazelton House](/Brazelton_House)** – Built in 1869, this Italianate‑style home features a distinctive cupola and ornate woodwork; it was later converted into a boarding house during the Great Depression.  

9. **[Brazelton House Hotel](/Brazelton_House_Hotel)** – Adjacent to the Brazelton House, this 1885 hotel served travelers on the **[U.S. Route 218](/U.S._Route_218)** corridor; its original wooden porch and hand‑crafted iron railings remain intact.  

10. **[Budde‑Singer Building](/Budde‑Singer_Building)** – A 1902 commercial structure that exemplifies early 20th‑century **[Steel Frame](/Steel_Construction)** construction; it originally housed a general merchandise store and later functioned as a bank branch.  

